## Round 12 — 2026-04-18

### Timestamp
2026-04-18 10:09 - 10:13

### Artifact Directory
`runtime_data/manual_sitl/zjg2/20260418_100949/`

### Observed Actual Behavior
- Takeoff completed at 40.43m, speed set to 12 m/s
- Scan state entered with 8 waypoints (50m margin)
- Geofence violation at (30.300447, 120.072516) — 21m outside boundary
- Emergency state entered, mission aborted

### Root Cause Analysis
The `_shrink_polygon` function was **fundamentally broken**:
- The normal computation `(by-ay, -(bx-ax))` computed a rotated edge vector, NOT an inward normal
- For the zjg2 polygon, ALL 11 shrunk vertices were OUTSIDE the original polygon
- The "100m shrink" was actually pushing vertices outward, placing scan waypoints outside the boundary
- This explained why all previous rounds (6-11) had persistent geofence violations regardless of margin

Secondary issue: even with correct shrink, the aircraft's turn overshoot at sweep endpoints near the polygon's sharp southern tip (vertices 7-8-9) causes the flight path to curve ~25m past waypoints.

### Code Changes Made
1. **`src/striker/flight/mission_geometry.py`** — Rewrote `_shrink_polygon()`:
   - Computes bisector of adjacent edge inward normals
   - Verifies direction points toward polygon centroid
   - Falls back to centroid-direction movement for degenerate cases
   - Safety check: if any vertex falls outside after shrink, uses binary search along centroid direction to find safe position
   - All shrunk vertices now guaranteed inside original polygon

2. **`src/striker/config/settings.py`** — Changed `scan_boundary_margin_m` default from 100.0 to 80.0
   - With correct shrink, 80m gives 94m minimum clearance (vs ~25m turn radius at 12m/s)
   - Verified: all inter-waypoint paths including 30% turn overshoot stay inside boundary

### Rationale
The polygon shrink was the root cause of ALL geofence violations since Round 6. The vertex averaging method was mathematically incorrect — it computed edge tangents, not inward normals. The fix uses proper bisector normals with centroid verification.

